# Data Engineering & Preparation {#data-prep}

Before exploratory analysis begins, the dataset must be checked for structural consistency and prepared for statistical use.

This preparation stage focuses on:

- Converting variables into appropriate analytical types  
- Verifying that expected workforce attributes were successfully merged  
- Preserving target-variable level ordering for later classification workflows  
- Creating a reusable base dataset for self-contained analysis chunks  

These steps do not materially alter the underlying workforce signals, but they ensure that later diagnostics and predictive models are built on a stable and reproducible analytical foundation.

## Data Preprocessing

Character variables are converted to factor representations where appropriate so they can be handled correctly in categorical summaries, visualization, encoding workflows, and predictive modeling.

This preprocessing step also ensures consistency across self-contained chunks, which is especially important for a multi-section analytical report intended for reproducible site rendering.

# Exploratory Workforce Analysis {#workforce-analysis}

This section examines the distributional behavior of the workforce dataset across continuous, ordinal, and categorical measures.

The aim is to identify:

- How employee values are distributed across key measures  
- Which variables show strong skewness or concentration  
- Where outliers may reflect meaningful employee subgroups  
- Whether the observed patterns resemble realistic workforce behavior  

These diagnostics provide the descriptive foundation for interpreting later correlation, stability, and target-relationship results.

## Variable Type Classification

Before plotting, numeric variables are divided into likely continuous variables and Likert-style variables based on the number of distinct observed values.

This distinction matters because variables measured on a wide numeric scale are best interpreted through histograms and density plots, while ordinal response-style variables are more appropriately summarized with count-based displays.

```{r 04-variable-type-classification, echo=FALSE}
hr_df <- base_df

numeric_vars <- hr_df %>%
  select(where(is.numeric)) %>%
  select(where(~ var(.x, na.rm = TRUE) > 0))

continuous_vars <- numeric_vars %>%
  select(where(~ dplyr::n_distinct(.x, na.rm = TRUE) > 15)) %>%
  names()

likert_vars <- setdiff(names(numeric_vars), continuous_vars)
```

## Variable Classification

For exploratory purposes, variables are organized into four practical groups based on both measurement scale and analytical role:

- **Continuous variables**, such as salary, tenure, distance, and workload-related measures  
- **Likert-style variables**, which capture employee perceptions, sentiment, support, and engagement  
- **Categorical variables**, which describe workforce composition and organizational context  
- **Target variables**, which represent the key organizational outcomes modeled later in the project  

This classification framework ensures that each variable group is explored using methods aligned with the type of signal it contains.

```{r 04-variable-selection, include=FALSE}
hr_df <- base_df

numeric_df <- get_numeric_df(hr_df)

continuous_vars <- numeric_df %>%
  select(where(~ dplyr::n_distinct(.x, na.rm = TRUE) > 15)) %>%
  names()

top_continuous <- numeric_df %>%
  summarise(across(all_of(continuous_vars), ~ var(.x, na.rm = TRUE))) %>%
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "name", values_to = "value") %>%
  arrange(desc(value)) %>%
  slice_head(n = 6) %>%
  pull(name)

