# Workforce Relationship Analysis {#correlation-analysis}

This section evaluates how numeric workforce variables relate to one another and whether those relationships suggest meaningful behavioral structure or problematic redundancy.

The analysis focuses on two complementary views:

- The **correlation matrix**, which summarizes overall pairwise relationships across numeric predictors  
- The **pairwise plot**, which shows shape, spread, and visible patterns for selected high-variance variables  

Together, these views help determine whether the dataset contains realistic clusters of related constructs while remaining stable enough for predictive modeling.

## Top Numeric Correlation Pairs

The original correlation matrix is useful as a diagnostic, but a full matrix becomes difficult to read when the dataset includes many workforce variables. For the main report, the more useful view is a ranked list of the strongest numeric relationships.

This plot removes the diagonal self-correlations and highlights the strongest non-duplicate numeric relationships. This makes the relationship structure easier to interpret without overstating weak associations.

```{r 05-correlation-plot, echo=FALSE}
hr_df <- base_df

numeric_data <- safe_numeric(hr_df)

corr_matrix <- cor(
  numeric_data,
  use = "complete.obs"
)

corr_df <- as.data.frame(as.table(corr_matrix)) %>%
  dplyr::rename(
    Var1 = Var1,
    Var2 = Var2,
    Correlation = Freq
  ) %>%
  dplyr::filter(as.character(Var1) < as.character(Var2)) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(
    Abs_Correlation = abs(Correlation),
    Direction = dplyr::case_when(
      Correlation >= 0 ~ "Positive",
      TRUE ~ "Negative"
    ),
    Relationship = paste0(
      clean_label(as.character(Var1)),
      " ↔ ",
      clean_label(as.character(Var2))
    )
  ) %>%
  dplyr::arrange(dplyr::desc(Abs_Correlation)) %>%
  dplyr::slice_head(n = 10) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(
    Relationship = stringr::str_wrap(Relationship, width = 32),
    Relationship = forcats::fct_reorder(Relationship, Abs_Correlation),
    Label = scales::number(Correlation, accuracy = 0.001)
  )

p <- ggplot(
  corr_df,
  aes(
    x = Abs_Correlation,
    y = Relationship,
    fill = Direction
  )
) +
  geom_col(
    width = 0.68,
    alpha = 0.95
  ) +
  geom_text(
    aes(label = Label),
    hjust = -0.10,
    size = 3.2,
    fontface = "bold",
    color = "#243447"
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c(
      "Positive" = "#2A9D8F",
      "Negative" = "#E76F51"
    )
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    labels = scales::number_format(accuracy = 0.1),
    limits = c(0, max(corr_df$Abs_Correlation, na.rm = TRUE) + 0.10),
    breaks = seq(0, 0.8, by = 0.1),
    expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.02))
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Strongest Numeric Relationships",
    subtitle = "Top non-duplicate correlations after removing self-correlations",
    x = "Absolute correlation strength",
    y = NULL,
    fill = NULL
  ) +
  theme_hr(11) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(
      face = "bold",
      size = 16,
      hjust = 0
    ),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(
      color = "#5A6B7C",
      size = 11,
      hjust = 0
    ),
    plot.title.position = "plot",
    axis.text.y = element_text(
      size = 8.3,
      face = "bold",
      color = "#243447",
      lineheight = 0.98
    ),
    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 9.5),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size = 10.5),
    legend.position = "top",
    legend.justification = "left",
    panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    plot.margin = margin(12, 48, 12, 10)
  ) +
  coord_cartesian(clip = "off")

print(p)

save_plot(
  p,
  "correlation_plot.png",
  width = 10.5,
  height = 5.9
)
```

### Interpreting Correlation Strength

Correlation coefficients describe the direction and magnitude of pairwise linear relationships. In workforce analytics, even modest correlations can be meaningful because employee outcomes are rarely driven by a single factor.

A practical interpretation framework for this analysis is:

- |r| ≈ 0.10 → weak but potentially meaningful relationship  
- |r| ≈ 0.15–0.20 → small but consistent association  
- |r| ≈ 0.25–0.35 → moderate relationship  
- |r| ≥ 0.50 → comparatively strong relationship and possible redundancy concern  

### 📊 Key Takeaways

