### Correlation Insights

The correlation results suggest that the dataset contains meaningful structure, but not excessive redundancy.

At higher thresholds, only a small number of relationships remain prominent, most notably the positive association between salary and tenure. This is consistent with expected workforce dynamics in which longer-tenured employees tend to earn more over time.

At more moderate thresholds, additional clustering appears among mental health and well-being measures, including stress, anxiety, depression, and absenteeism-related variables. These relationships suggest that the dataset captures coherent psychological and behavioral dimensions rather than isolated indicators.

Smaller but still interpretable relationships also emerge among monitoring and privacy-related variables, reinforcing the idea that these constructs contribute signal while remaining secondary to broader engagement and well-being patterns.

Taken together, the correlation structure reflects a realistic workforce system in which outcomes are shaped by several interacting dimensions rather than a handful of overpowering predictors.

