# Model Stability Diagnostics {#vif-section}

Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) analysis is used to assess whether predictors contain overlapping linear signal that could reduce model stability or interpretability.

The diagnostics are separated into:

- Numeric predictors  
- Categorical predictors after dummy encoding  

This allows the analysis to distinguish between continuous overlap and redundancy introduced through categorical expansion.

## VIF for Numeric Predictors

This diagnostic evaluates whether numeric predictors contribute largely independent information or whether some variables are redundant enough to inflate variance in model estimation.

Given the modest correlation structure observed earlier, the expectation is that numeric multicollinearity will remain limited.

```{r 07-vif-numeric, echo=FALSE}
library(car)

hr_df <- base_df

numeric_data <- safe_numeric(hr_df)

numeric_data$.__dummy__ <- rnorm(nrow(numeric_data))

vif_model <- lm(.__dummy__ ~ ., data = numeric_data)

aliased <- is.na(coef(vif_model))

if (any(aliased)) {
  numeric_data <- numeric_data[, !names(numeric_data) %in% names(coef(vif_model))[aliased]]
  vif_model <- lm(.__dummy__ ~ ., data = numeric_data)
}

vif_values <- car::vif(vif_model)

vif_df <- tibble(
  Variable = names(vif_values),
  VIF = as.numeric(vif_values)
) %>%
  mutate(Variable = gsub("`|'", "", Variable)) %>%
  arrange(desc(VIF))

vif_df <- vif_df %>%
  mutate(Variable = clean_label(Variable))

p <- ggplot(vif_df, aes(x = VIF, y = reorder(Variable, VIF), fill = VIF)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "#A8DADC", high = "#1D3557") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 5, linetype = "dashed", color = "#E63946") +
  theme_hr(10) +
  theme(
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 7),
    legend.position = "none"
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Variance Inflation Factor (Numeric Predictors)",
    x = "Variance Inflation Factor",
    y = NULL
  )

print(p)
save_plot(p, "vif_numeric.png", 9, 6)
```

### 📊 Key Takeaways

```{=html}
<div class="takeaway-box">

<p>
Most numeric predictors fall within acceptable VIF thresholds, indicating limited multicollinearity concerns.
</p>

<p>
A small number of variables show moderate inflation, which may reflect overlapping constructs rather than true redundancy. These variables should be monitored but do not currently require removal.
</p>

</div>
```

## VIF for Categorical Predictors

Categorical multicollinearity is assessed after dummy encoding factor variables into indicator columns.

This step is especially important because redundancy can arise not only from conceptual overlap between variables, but also from the way multiple levels of the same categorical construct are represented.

