## Addressing Age Group Multicollinearity

The categorical VIF results indicate that the original age-group encoding introduces unnecessary redundancy across several dummy variables.

This is expected when multiple mutually exclusive levels of a single ordered construct are encoded in detail. To reduce that redundancy while preserving analytical meaning, the original age groups are collapsed into broader career-stage categories:

- Early-Career  
- Mid-Career  
- Senior-Career  

This simplifies the age structure, improves model stability, and retains the substantive workforce interpretation of age-related differences.

```{r 07-update-age-groups, fig.show="hold", echo=FALSE}
hr_df <- base_df

hr_df <- hr_df %>%
  mutate(
    age_group = case_when(
      age_group %in% c("16-19", "20-24", "25-34") ~ "Early-Career",
      age_group %in% c("35-44", "45-54") ~ "Mid-Career",
      age_group %in% c("55-64", "65+") ~ "Senior-Career",
      TRUE ~ as.character(age_group)
    ),
    age_group = factor(
      age_group,
      levels = c("Early-Career", "Mid-Career", "Senior-Career")
    )
  )
```

## Updated Categorical VIF Check

After collapsing age into broader career stages, categorical multicollinearity is recalculated to verify that the feature space is more stable and less redundant.

This second check confirms whether the adjustment resolves the earlier inflation without removing the workforce signal contributed by age-related structure.

